  "explanations": [
    {
      "text": "In a German main clause, the finite verb—the verb form that changes for the subject—normally goes in second position. This is called Verbzweitstellung. In `Anna trinkt heute Kaffee`, `trinkt` is second: first comes `Anna`, then the verb.",
      "title": "Verb-second in German main clauses"
    },
    {
      "text": "The first position can be something other than the subject, like a time word. If `Heute` is first, the verb still must be second: `Heute trinkt Anna Kaffee`. This is different from English, where you usually say “Today, Anna drinks coffee,” without moving the subject after the verb.",
      "title": "When something else comes first"
    }
  ],
  "questions": [
